<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910801-0038</DOCNO><DOCID>910801-0038.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Motorola Inc.:   Raytheon, Lockheed Units   To Join in Satellite System</HL><DATE>08/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><CO>   LK MOT RTN</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)DIVERSIFIED TECHNOLOGY (DTC)</IN><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)ILLINOIS (IL)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Motorola Inc. said its satellite communications unitsigned a letter of mutual understanding with Lockheed Corp.'sCommercial Space Co. unit and Raytheon Co.'s equipmentdivision.   Under terms of the letter, Motorola said that Raytheonwill enter negotiations for the development, design andproduction of main mission antennae for the Iridium system, asatellite-based system for personal telecommunications.</LP><TEXT>   Motorola, an automotive and industrial electronicsequipment maker based in Schaumberg, Ill., said the systemwill use its space technology with earth-based wirelesscommunications expertise. The system will employ low earthorbiting satellites to provide world-wide, hand-held portableand mobile telecommunications service.   Current plans call for the team to begin launching theIridium system's 77 satellites in 1994, Motorola added.</TEXT></DOC>